irca 1318","1235":"1235","1213":"1213","1233":"1233","1342":"1342","after 24 December 1262":"na 24 december 1262","1318":"1318","1306":"1306","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Egerton, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wrenbury, Cheshire, England":"Wrenbury, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Northwich, Cheshire, England":"Northwich, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1235–about 1318":"1235–about 1318","1235–1318":"1235–1318","1233–1306":"1233–1306","1250–1342":"1250–1342","1259–1318":"1259–1318","1220–1262":"1220–1262","1162–1213":"1162–1213","Abt 1238":"about 1238","1220":"1220","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","1162":"1162","1259":"1259","about 1318":"about 1318","1235":"1235","1213":"1213","1233":"1233","1342":"1342","after 24 December 1262":"after 24 December 1262","1318":"1318","1306":"1306","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Egerton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Wrenbury, Cheshire, England":"Wrenbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Northwich, Cheshire, England":"Northwich, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Courtenay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Courtney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Courtney","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Courtenay near Sens in northern France, or some other place similarly named, from the name of a Gallo-Roman landlord, <i>Curtenus</i> (a derivative of Latin <i>curtus</i> ‘short’) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>.","Irish: English surname adopted for <b>Ó Curnáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Curnán’</i>, an Old Irish personal name based on a diminutive of <i>corn</i> ‘horn’.","History: A family of this name (see 1 above) can be traced back to Athon de Courtenay, who lived in Courtenay in Loiret in the early 11th century. Renaud de Courtenay held land in Devon in the 12th century, and the family later held the title of Earls of Devon following the marriage of Hugh de Courtenay to Margaret de Bohun, granddaughter of King Edward I, in 1325."]}]},{"name":"Catherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["equivalent of   Katherine  , also occasionally used in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Catharine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Catherine de Courtenay was born in 1235, in Wrenbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir William de Courtenay, was 16 and her mother, Joan Basset, was 73. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Richard Wrenbury. She died about 1318, in her hometown, at the age of 84."},"et":{"1235–about 1318":"1235–umbes 1318","1235–1318":"1235–1318","1233–1306":"1233–1306","1250–1342":"1250–1342","1259–1318":"1259–1318","1220–1262":"1220–1262","1162–1213":"1162–1213","Abt 1238":"umbes 1238","1220":"1220","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","1162":"1162","1259":"1259","about 1318":"umbes 1318","1235":"1235","1213":"1213","1233":"1233","1342":"1342","after 24 December 1262":"pärast 24. detsembrit 1262","1318":"1318","1306":"1306","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Egerton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wrenbury, Cheshire, England":"Wrenbury, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northwich, Cheshire, England":"Northwich, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1235–about 1318":"1235–noin 1318","1235–1318":"1235–1318","1233–1306":"1233–1306","1250–1342":"1250–1342","1259–1318":"1259–1318","1220–1262":"1220–1262","1162–1213":"1162–1213","Abt 1238":"noin 1238","1220":"1220","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","1162":"1162","1259":"1259","about 1318":"no